ions, Preferences and Musical Taste in the Staegemann- Olfers Salon in Nineteenth-Century Berlin -- t13 Josephine Lang and the Salon in Southern Germany -- t14 Jessie Hillebrand and Musical Life in 1870s Florence -- t15 An Invitation to 309 Beacon Street: Clara Kathleen Rogers and her Boston Salon -- t16 ‘Too Much Playing Four Hands!’: Ernst von Dohnányi’s European Salon in the United States of the 1950s -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book reconsiders the significance of the salon as a social and cultural phenomenon and as a source of artistic innovation and exchange in the long nineteenth century.This collection explores the idea of music in the salon during the long nineteenth century, both as a socio-cultural phenomenon, and as a source of artistic innovation and exchange. Drawing on a wide range of scholarly approaches,this book uses the idea of the salon as a springboard to examine issues such as gender, religion, biography and performance; to explore the ways in which the salon was represented in different media; and to showcase the heterogeneity of the salon through a selection of case studies. It offers fresh considerations of familiar salons in large cultural centres, as well as insights into lesser-known salons in both Europe and the United States. Bringing together an international group of scholars, the collection underscores the enduring impact of the European musical salon. ANJA BUNZEL holds a research position at the Czech Academy of Sciences. She gained her PhD in Musicology from Maynooth University and has published on Johanna Kinkel and nineteenth-century salon culture in both English and German. NATASHA LOGES is Head of Postgraduate Programmes at the Royal College of Music, London. Her publications include Brahms in the Home and the Concert Hall (Cambridge, 2014) and Brahms and his Poets (Boydell Press, 2017). She is a pianist, broadcaster and critic. Contributors: Maren Bagge, PéterBozó, Anja Bunzel, Katie A. Callam, Beatrix Darmstädter, Mary Anne Garnett, Harald Krebs, Clemens Kreutzfeldt, Veronika Kusz, Natasha Loges, Jennifer Ronyak, Kirsten Santos Rutschman, R. Larry Todd, Katharina Uhde, Michael Uhde, Harry White, Petra Wilhelmy-Dollinger, Susan Youens  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusic in the homexSocial aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusic in the homexSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusicxSocial aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusicxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aSalonsxHistoryy19th centuryzEurope. 0aSalonsxHistoryy20th centuryzUnited States. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aEurope.  aMusical salon culture.  aUnited States.  aartistic innovation.  acase studies.  agender.  along nineteenth century.  aperformance.  asocio-cultural phenomenon.1 aBagge, Maren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBozó, Péter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunzel, Anja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunzel, Anja, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCallam, Katie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarmstädter, Beatrix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarnett, Mary Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrebs, Harald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreutzfeldt, Clemens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKusz, Veronika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoges, Natasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc